{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502165"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:40:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:40:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1829"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1829"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.51,0.21,0.06,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1829"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43636"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1829"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1829"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28647"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"932"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5757"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39600"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43636"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a one-month history of increasing breathlessness. His medical history is unremarkable apart from a chest infection two months ago and some rib fractures sustained in a motor vehicle crash when he was 22. He takes no regular medications. He has a 15 pack-year smoking history and drinks two cans of beer a day. He migrated from India at the age of 30. On respiratory examination, there is dullness to percussion at the left base with reduced breath sounds. A chest CT is performed (Images 1 - 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Squamous cell carcinoma of the lung","Diaphragmatic hernia","Empyema","Aspergilloma","Tuberculosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAny of the listed conditions could present with breathlessness. Narrowing the differentials in this question centres around the interpretation of the images provided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiaphragmatic hernia \u003C/strong\u003Ethat is acquired rather than congenital is a rare condition that most often is due to diaphragmatic penetrating injury and involves the protrusion of abdominal contents into the thoracic cavity, most commonly appearing on the left hand side due to the protective effects of the liver on the right.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s past history of a motor vehicle accident with rib fractures many years prior increases the diagnostic probability, with the subsequent CT scans showing a large space-occupying lesion in the left chest. The coronal view shows that the lateral part of the left hemi-diaphram is missing and abdominal contents have ascended into the chest. The transverse view shows pockets of gas in the stomach and colon within the chest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma of the lung \u003C/strong\u003Emay fit with the patient\u0027s history of smoking, however upon chest imaging squamous cell carcinoma would classically present as a lesion arising centrally within the lungs, from a bronchi or extending into one.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpyema \u003C/strong\u003Eon imaging would typically present with a unilateral whiteout section of the pleura that can resemble a pleural effusion. Although the patient does have a history of respiratory infection, there is no indication of such a lesion in the imaging provided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspergilloma \u003C/strong\u003Eare a form of pulmonary infection by the fungi \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus fumigatus. \u003C/em\u003EThey typically will present in patients with underlying cavities in the lungs, caused by previous pulmonary pathologies. On imaging they usually appear as a mass within a cavity in lung parenchyma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis (TB) , \u003C/strong\u003Ealthough on the differentials for this patient due to his presentation and his endemic country of birth, is not consistent with the imaging provided. Pulmonary TB\u0027s classic lesion is a localised caseating granuloma, which subsequently forms a ghon lesion upon calcification. The imaging provided shows no focal lesions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Diaphragmatic herniation is a rare differential for breathlessness in an adult, most likely to occur subsequent to a penetrating injury to the diaphragm or blunt abdominal trauma."],"references":["Blitz M, Louie BE. Chronic traumatic diaphragmatic hernia. Surg Clin. 2009; 19491-500."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28647"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1829"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15624"},{"type":"media","id":"15625"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15624"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2b5b8aef-b19f-48e7-ac14-52f05287efe5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2b5b8aef-b19f-48e7-ac14-52f05287efe5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":487,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"15625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15625"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app